{
  "answer": "**The Āṅgirasa Smṛti (a single-chapter work of 1792 paragraphs) addresses prayascittas (penances or expiations) extensively in its \"Later Āṅgirasa Text\" (starting around paragraph [p-90b022]), framed as a Dharmaśāstra on *dharma*, assemblies (*pariṣad*), and penances (*prāyaścitta*).**[^1]\n\n**General prayascittas for women are prescribed at half the standard rate for intentional sins (Ang_2,10.20), with further reductions (to one quarter) for women alongside children, the elderly, and eunuchs.**[^2] This follows detailed rules on assemblies prescribing penances proportional to sin gravity, caste, age, and intent (Ang_2,1–10). Women are also covered in specific cases like adultery, remarriage (*puṇarbhū*), or self-immolation with a non-husband (*sahagamana*), often requiring travel to sacred sites (e.g., Setu/Rāmeśvaram), vows like Cāndrāyaṇa or Taptakṛcchra, baths, *Pañcagavya*, and Gāyatrī recitation.[^3][^4]\n\nNo dedicated standalone \"section\" exists solely on \"prayascittas for women\"; rules are integrated into broader penance chapters (esp. Ang_2,2–12) and earlier case law on marriage/adultery (paras. ~[p-9684fe]–[p-a7cedd]). Menstruating women (*rajasvalāḥ*) are noted as ritually impure but without unique prayascittas here.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-90b022).\n\n[^2]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1, [p-83ee9c](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-83ee9c).\n\n[^3]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1, [p-9684fe](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-9684fe).\n\n[^4]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1, [p-73aeea](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-73aeea).\n\n[^5]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1, [p-d769c5](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-d769c5) (work-level wiki trigram).",
